Shortly after the fall of the Republic, and per· haps‚ as has been supposed, through the intluence of the jurist Labeo (Dig. 15. 5. 1. 1;ib. ro pr.; ib. 2o pn), the Roman contract system received a considerable extension by a more general recognition of this principle. Every agreement, even though not belonging to any of the three hitherto established classes of contract, in which an act on the one side was the consideration for an act on the other, was at length, though only by a gradual development, held enforceable by action at the suit of that party who had performed all to which he was bound under its terms : ‘sedet si in alium contractum res non transeat, subsit tamen causa, ele· ganter Aristo Celso respondit, esse obligationem, ut puta dedi tibi rem, ut mihi aliam dares, dedi, ut aliquid facias, hoc συνάλλαγμα esse, et hinc nasci civilem obligationem’ Dig. a. 14. 17. a. The essential marks of such actionable agreement thus are (1)mutuality; there must be a συνάλλαγμα, e. g. an act must be promised on the one side in return for an act on the other; (2) there must have been performance on one side; the mere bilateral agreement gives rise to no civil obligation: ‘item emptio ac venditio nuda consentientium voluntate contrahitur, permutatio autem ex re tradita initium obligationi praebet, alioquin, si res nondum tradita sit, nudo consensu constitui obligationem dicemus, quod in his duntaxat receptum est, quae nomen suum habent, ut in emptione, venditione, conductione, mandato’ Dig. ro 4 r. 2.

Such agreements are by the modern civilians called innominate (real) contracts ; the Romans themselves do not call thern ‘contractus,' and in fact have no general designation for them.
